g a Java helper in the library package to generate the right test class. \\\\n\\\\nI’m thinking about using a Java test file to import the necessary classes, but I need to ensure it compiles correctly and handles execution reporting.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Analyzing JaCoCo counters and coverage**\\\\n\\\\nI'm pondering why the generated lambda isn't showing counters in JaCoCo. Is it filtering due to Kotlin's generated code without line mapping? I think the previous attempt to execute the lambda while inlining might not have worked. Also, I need to consider if the dynamic-access coverage is only checking for line coverage rather than any executed code lines. \\\\n\\\\nI could implement a JaCoCo XML normalizer to help, but that's a bit hacky and might not meet standards. Alternatively, I could update the build logic to properly parse SMAP, which seems like a more robust solution.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Addressing dynamic-access coverage**\\\\n\\\\nI'm working on a fix for parsing dynamic-access frames in Kotlin inline generated classes. I need to utilize the library's SourceDebugExtension SMAP to accurately map output line 112 back to source line 54 for proper coverage checks. However, the user wants me to focus on the active class, which is a different direction. It seems they expect only tests, not infrastructure details. \\\\n\\\\nI'm considering that the \\\\\\\"none\\\\\\\" response may indicate that our test didn't trigger. So, I think it’s a good idea to add a behavioral test using the public coroutine API to confirm this!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Testing JaCoCo configuration**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about JaCoCo and how the XML report shows the `safeCtor$1` class with no methods after the existing tests. It's a filter that doesn't rely on execution, so direct invocation won't alter the report structure. Therefore, I conclude that it won't help. I'm considering whether we could adjust JaCoCo to include the option \\\\\\\"includeKotlinGeneratedClasses = true\\\\\\\" for better coverage reporting. Let's explore that idea further!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_sBRrP98KZo8ta7BLuqFXEq0A|fc_09d8b5e4b3d86acf0169f981d32c10819c9464ca1a5d2159cb\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"grep -R \\\"includeKotlin\\\" -n ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.jacoco* 2>/dev/null | head\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 1869, \"output\": 1606, \"cacheRead\": 50176, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 53651, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777959354454, \"responseId\": \"resp_09d8b5e4b3d86acf0169f981bb13e8819c91b68d2c94c2dbfa\"}}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.jetbrains.kotlinx:kotlinx-coroutines-core-jvm:1.6.4/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-05T05-29-36-273448Z.log:5720:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Evaluating Kotlin metadata and testing**\\n\\nI'm considering why the class isn't in Kotlin metadata. It seems the test compile could fail due to unresolved references. Using Java's `Class.forName` might be restricted, which isn't ideal. I wonder if I could create a reference in Java using `$`. There's also the idea of adding a Java helper in the library package to generate the right test class. \\n\\nI’m thinking about using a Java test file to import the necessary classes, but I need to ensure it compiles correctly and handles execution reporting.\\n\\n**Analyzing JaCoCo counters and coverage**\\n\\nI'm pondering why the generated lambda isn't showing counters in JaCoCo. Is it filtering due to Kotlin's generated code without line mapping? I think the previous attempt to execute the lambda while inlining might not have